---
import type { Book } from '@rtp/schema';

interface Props {
  slug: string;
  book: Book;
}

const { slug, book } = Astro.props;

const repo = 'https://github.com/markselby9/readtheplaces.com';
const issue = `${repo}/issues/new?template=add-a-place.md&title=${encodeURIComponent(`Adopt: ${book.title}`)}`;
---

<section class="adopt">
  <p class="flag">Open for adoption</p>

  <h2>Nobody has mapped this book yet.</h2>

  <p class="lede">
    It is listed because it can be done: the text is public domain, the city is real, and the places
    in it are findable. What it needs is somebody who has read it.
  </p>

  <h3>What adopting a book means</h3>

  <p>
    Not writing code. Reading a novel you probably already love, and answering, for a dozen of its
    places, the one question a machine cannot: <strong>why does this place matter?</strong>
  </p>

  <ol class="steps">
    <li>
      <code>bun run fetch-text {slug}</code>
      <p>
        Downloads the text from {book.rights.textSource}. Every quote you write will be checked
        against it.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>bun run extract {slug} --geocode</code>
      <p>
        Hands you a queue of every place the book mentions, with the sentence it appears in, where
        it falls in the text, and a suggested coordinate. It never writes a waypoint. It writes a
        worklist.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Take one. Look at the pin on a map.</strong>
      <p>
        The geocoder is confidently wrong all the time. It once placed Bourton, the Dalloways'
        country house, in Hillingdon. Only a reader catches that.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Say how sure you are, and why it matters.</strong>
      <p>
        Two or three sentences about the novel, not about what is there today. If the author never
        gave an address, say so. An honest <em>inferred</em> beats a confident mistake.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Choose the book's colour.</strong>
      <p>
        A colour here is a quotation. <em>Mrs Dalloway</em> is green because she “laid her green dress
        on her bed”. Find the line in this novel where a colour means something, and the build will check
        the line is really there.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p class="actions">
    <a class="primary" href={issue}>Claim this book →</a>
    <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md`}>How contributing works</a>
  </p>

  <div class="rights">
    <h3>Rights, as far as we have checked</h3>
    <dl>
      <div>
        <dt>Work</dt>
        <dd>{book.rights.originalWork}</dd>
      </div>
      {
        book.rights.translation && (
          <div>
            <dt>Translation</dt>
            <dd>{book.rights.translation}</dd>
          </div>
        )
      }
      <div>
        <dt>Text</dt>
        <dd>
          <a href={book.rights.textSourceUrl}>{book.rights.textSource}</a>
        </dd>
      </div>
      <div>
        <dt>Territory</dt>
        <dd>{book.rights.territoryNotes}</dd>
      </div>
    </dl>
    <p class="small">
      We say <strong>rights-reviewed</strong>, never “licence-clean”. Public domain is
      jurisdiction-specific, and the entries above still say TODO because nobody has finished
      checking them. Doing that is part of adopting the book.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .adopt {
    max-width: 42rem;
    padding-block: var(--s7) var(--s9);
  }

  .flag {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.25rem 0.6rem;
    border: 1px dashed var(--ink-3);
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--ink-2);
  }

  h2 {
    margin-block: var(--s4) var(--s4);
    font-size: var(--step-3);
    font-weight: 300;
    line-height: 1.08;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }

  h3 {
    margin-block: var(--s7) var(--s4);
    font-size: var(--step-1);
    font-weight: 400;
  }

  .lede {
    font-size: var(--step-1);
    font-weight: 300;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink-2);
  }

  p {
    color: var(--ink-2);
  }

  .steps {
    margin: var(--s5) 0 var(--s7);
    padding: 0;
    list-style: none;
    counter-reset: step;
  }
  .steps li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 2.4rem;
    padding-bottom: var(--s5);
    counter-increment: step;
  }
  .steps li::before {
    content: counter(step);
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0.1rem;
    width: 1.6rem;
    height: 1.6rem;
    display: grid;
    place-items: center;
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    border-radius: 50%;
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--ink-3);
  }
  .steps code {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--s2);
    padding: 0.2rem 0.45rem;
    background: var(--paper-3);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, monospace;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
  }
  .steps p {
    margin-top: var(--s2);
    font-size: var(--step--1);
    font-family: var(--sans);
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--ink-3);
  }

  .actions {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--s5);
    align-items: center;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-block: var(--s6);
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: var(--step--1);
  }
  .actions .primary {
    padding: 0.6rem 1rem;
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--paper);
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .rights {
    margin-top: var(--s8);
    padding-top: var(--s5);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .rights dl {
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--s4);
    margin-bottom: var(--s5);
  }
  .rights dt {
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--ink-3);
    margin-bottom: 0.2rem;
  }
  .rights dd {
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: var(--step--1);
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--ink-2);
  }
  .small {
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: var(--step--1);
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--ink-3);
  }
</style>
